e weight of the upper body when sitting and standing"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einnominate bone\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as the hip bone, is a large, irregular bone that forms part of the pelvis. It is composed of three parts: the ilium, ischium, and pubis. The primary function of the innominate bone is to \u003Cstrong\u003Esupport the weight of the upper body when sitting and standing\u003C/strong\u003E. It also provides attachment points for muscles and ligaments that facilitate movement and stability of the pelvis and lower limbs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe innominate bone does not \u003Cstrong\u003Efacilitate the movement of the shoulder joint\u003C/strong\u003E, as this is the function of the scapula and clavicle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the rib cage \u003Cstrong\u003Eprotects the thoracic organs\u003C/strong\u003E, the innominate bone is not involved in this function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexion of the elbow joint\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily facilitated by the humerus, radius, and ulna, not the innominate bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emovement of the wrist joint\u003C/strong\u003E involves the radius, ulna, and carpal bones, rather than the innominate bone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The innominate bone, also known as the hip bone, is composed of the ilium, ischium, and pubis.","The primary function of the innominate bone is to support the weight of the upper body when sitting and standing.","The innominate bone provides attachment for various muscles and ligaments, contributing to movement and stability of the pelvis and lower limbs."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59403"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18243"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59403"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T08:04:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T08:05:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10957"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73926"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"